Source: SherLIiC: A Typed Event-Focused Lexical Inference Benchmark for Evaluating Natural Language Inference
Definition: Given two sentences, P and Q, determine if P is the premise and Q the hypothesis or Q is the premise of P. If P is the premise and Q the hypothesis, the answer would be "PQ". If Q is the premise and P the hypothesis, the answer would be "QP". If P and Q are not a premise-hypothesis pair, answer "NO". If P and Q are premise-hypothesis pairs of each other, that is, both PQ and QP are valid, then answer "YES".

Positive Examples.Q: location[B] is one of city in location[A]
Positive Examples.explanation: Location B being a city of location A(Sentence P), implies that it is also the centered in location A(Sentence Q). Location B is the centered in location A(Sentence Q), implies that Location B is a city of location A(Sentence P). Since both are true, the answer is "YES".

Employer B outperforms employer A (Sentence P) does not imply that it will have employer A(Sentence Q). But if employer B is having employer A(Sentence Q), it implies that employer B is outperforming employer A(Sentence P). Hence, the answer is QP.

Negative Examples.explanation: There is no relation between A and B so the answer should be "NO"

Organization_founder[A] decides to invade location[B] implies organization_founder[A] is fighting location[B] but organization_founder[A] is fighting location[B] does not imply Organization_founder[A] decides to invade location[B]. So the order is PQ and not QP.
